  "descriptions": [
    {
      "text": "悪の博士ロボトニックは、世界を支配するための新しい計画を立てました。彼はモビウス山に新しい武器、ベジ-O-フォートレスを建設し、それを使ってすべての生き物をロボットに変えています。ソニックは要塞に忍び込み、ロボトニックを止めようとします。\n\nソニックをピンボールとして4つの危険なレベルで使いましょう。ポイントを獲得し、リングを集め、カオスエメラルドを集め、各レベルの最後にボスを倒しましょう。",
      "lang": "ja",
      "source": "romu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sonic Spinball, also known as Sonic the Hedgehog Spinball, is a 1993 pinball video game developed by Sega Technical Institute and published by Sega for the Sega Genesis. It is a spin-off of the Sonic the Hedgehog series. Players control Sonic the Hedgehog, who must stop Doctor Robotnik from enslaving the population in a giant pinball-like mechanism. The game is set in a series of pinball machine-like environments with Sonic acting as the pinball.\nIt was developed by the American staff of Sega Technical Institute, as the Japanese staff was occupied with developing Sonic the Hedgehog 3 and Sonic & Knuckles. When Sega management realized that Sonic 3 would not be completed in time for the 1993 holiday shopping season, they commissioned another Sonic game. After a hasty nine-month development, Sonic Spinball was released for the Sega Genesis in November 1993, with ports for the Game Gear and Master System releasing in 1994.\nSonic Spinball received mixed reviews, with critics praising the novelty and graphics but criticizing the controls. A second pinball game, Sonic Pinball Party, was released in 2003, and a Sonic Spinball spinning rollercoaster opened in Alton Towers theme park, in 20",
      "lang": "en",
      "source": "wikipedia_en"
    }
  ],
  "first_release_date": "1993-12-10",
